{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614872","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614872"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:51:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:51:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16379"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16379","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16379"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.35,0.04,0.13,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9070"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74760"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9070"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16379"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7114"},{"type":"tags","id":"10336"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21570"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA medical student is studying the histology of the cerebral cortex under a microscope. They observe a population of neurons with distinctive morphology that form the primary output cells of the cortex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most characteristic feature of pyramidal neurons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple axons emerging from the cell body","Have both apical and basal dendrites","Spherical cell body without processes","Absence of dendritic spines","Inhibitory neurotransmitter release"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPyramidal neurons are the principal excitatory neurons of the cerebral cortex and hippocampus. Their most distinctive morphological feature is their dendritic organisation. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaving both apical and basal dendrites\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic - the apical dendrite extends toward the pial surface while multiple basal dendrites branch around the cell body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple axons\u003C/strong\u003E emerging from the cell body is incorrect as neurons typically have only one axon that emerges from the axon hillock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Espherical cell body without processes\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as pyramidal neurons have a distinctive triangular soma with multiple processes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsence of dendritic spines\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as pyramidal neurons are characterised by numerous dendritic spines, which are sites of excitatory synaptic input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibitory neurotransmitter release\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as pyramidal neurons are excitatory, primarily using glutamate as their neurotransmitter. Inhibitory neurons in the cortex are typically interneurons that use GABA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe unique morphology of pyramidal neurons, particularly their dendritic organisation, allows them to integrate inputs from multiple sources and serve as the main output neurons of the cortex. Their apical dendrites receive inputs from distant cortical layers while basal dendrites receive local inputs.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pyramidal neurons are characterized by a triangular cell body and both apical and basal dendrites.","Pyramidal neurons are the primary excitatory neurons of the cerebral cortex and hippocampus.","The apical dendrite extends toward the cortical surface while basal dendrites branch around the cell body."],"references":["Spruston N. Pyramidal neurons: dendritic structure and synaptic integration. Nat Rev Neurosci. 2008 Mar;9(3):206-21. doi: 10.1038/nrn2286. PMID: 18270515.","Benavides-Piccione R, Blazquez-Llorca L, Kastanauskaite A, Fernaud-Espinosa I, Tapia-Gonz\u00e1lez S, DeFelipe J. Key morphological features of human pyramidal neurons. Cereb Cortex. 2024 May 2;34(5):bhae180. doi: 10.1093/cercor/bhae180. PMID: 38745556; PMCID: PMC11094408.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16379"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-26T21:53:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:00:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9070"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"at